            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/></p>
            <p>OFFICE OF THE<lb/>
                Hebrew Union College.<lb/>
                Cincinnati&#44; Sept. 15 1876<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. Mr. Morrais<lb/>
                Dear Sir &#38; Colleague.<lb/></p>
            <p>It was my duty and<lb/> would have been my pleasure to<lb/> answer your kind notes to me<lb/> ere this&#44; but &#91;Hebrew&#93; my time<lb/> is so parceled out&#44; that I am its<lb/> slave.  While in the East the heat so<lb/> completely reduced me&#44; that I was<lb/> forced to return home without<lb/> having seen anybody.  Since my return<lb/> I had to go over the whole ground<lb/> of this year&#39;s course in the college&#44;<lb/> viz over &#91;Hebrew&#93; in the &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; over<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; in &#91;Hebrew&#93; and &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> with the &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; besides the portions<lb/> in &#91;Hebrew&#93; and &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; which kept me<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>steadily tied down at the books.<lb/>  This is my excuse.<lb/></p>
            <p>Luzzatto&#39;s Aram. Grammar<lb/> has been translated in English<lb/> by Goldammer&#44; and we expect<lb/> the book every day.  What is<lb/> most needed now is a rabbinical<lb/> lexicon for students&#44; to be brief<lb/> and comprehensive.  We have<lb/> the &#91;Hebrew&#93; and &#91;Hebrew&#93; with<lb/> Buxdorf&#39;s and Landau&#39;s additions&#44;<lb/> also &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; Sachs&#39; and<lb/> Pereles&#39; contributions&#44; Nock&#39;s dictiona&#45;<lb/>ry&#44; and there is now appearing in<lb/> Breslau Levy&#39;s Rabbinical<lb/> Lexicon &#40;in German&#41;&#44; to take these<lb/> together with the existing Aram.<lb/> lexica&#44; and extract a brief lexicon<lb/> for students&#44; would be a meritorious<lb/> work.  Next we should have<lb/> an English translation of the &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>and &#91;Hebrew&#93; as introductions to<lb/> the philosophical literature.<lb/></p>
            <p>We have now in the<lb/> college 24 students&#44; ten in the<lb/> class of this year&#44; and 14 in my<lb/> class&#44; who take Talmud &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44;<lb/> mishnah &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; Bible &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> and &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; Mam. Grammar<lb/> and history.  Later in the season<lb/> I will take &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  It keeps me<lb/> busy&#44; and yet my opponents cry<lb/> honor&#44; because I do what they<lb/> neither could nor would do.<lb/></p>
            <p>I believe&#44; if the Philad.<lb/> congregations come into the Union&#44;<lb/> that the Maimonides College<lb/> could be re&#45;opened as a Preparatory<lb/> with four classes for four years<lb/> as the one I am at now&#44; and at<lb/> the next meeting of the Council<lb/> a committee could be appointed<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>to carry this into effect.  In my<lb/> opinion&#44; a teacher having but two<lb/> hours a day to teach&#44; must have<lb/> no more htan 12 to 14 students.<lb/>  As the matter stands now&#44; our<lb/> Preparatory will be full in two<lb/> years.  We have but two students<lb/> from the East&#44; consequently a<lb/> Preparatory in the East&#44; i.e. In<lb/> Philadelphia might be just as<lb/> well filled in three to four<lb/> years. &#91;Hebrew&#93;.<lb/></p>
            <p>I would have to<lb/> write you much more&#44; but must<lb/> close here with my best wishes&#44;<lb/> my assurance of highest regard<lb/> and a heartfelt &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  Yours<lb/></p>
            <p>Isaac M Wise<lb/></p>
        </body>
